<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1041,2041]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,153,647]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="275" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1942,1968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hill" authorityYear="1973" box="[282,413,1943,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evanirvana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[282,413,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">Evanirvana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hill, B. G." box="[623,750,1942,1968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="273" pagination="78 - 79" refId="ref5589" refString="Hill, B. G. (1973) A new genus of Cicadellidae from Brazil. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 75 (1), 78 - 79." type="journal article" year="1973">Hill (1973)</bibRefCitation>
based on two female specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hill, 1973" authorityName="Hill" authorityYear="1973" box="[1164,1389,1942,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evanirvana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis box="[1164,1181,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1197,1261,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">aurea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hill, B. G." box="[1270,1389,1942,1968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="273" pagination="78 - 79" refId="ref5589" refString="Hill, B. G. (1973) A new genus of Cicadellidae from Brazil. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 75 (1), 78 - 79." type="journal article" year="1973">Hill, 1973</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<typeStatus box="[151,249,1978,2004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">holotype</typeStatus>
from Angra dos Reis, State of 
<collectingRegion box="[622,792,1978,2004]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
and the 
<typeStatus box="[898,994,1979,2005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">paratype</typeStatus>
from Joinville, State of 
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
, southeastern and southern regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[618,689,2014,2040]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="273">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, respectively. We interpret the male specimen described herein as tentatively being conspecific with the female 
<typeStatus box="[664,762,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hill" authorityYear="1973" box="[800,896,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evanirvana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis box="[800,896,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">E. aurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male resembles the 
<typeStatus box="[1184,1282,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">holotype</typeStatus>
in having the crown anterior margin rounded and the disc with a dark W-shaped macula. The collecting locality in 
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Rio de Janeiro State</collectingRegion>
is also not far from the type locality. However, some striking differences between the male and female should be noted: (1) our male specimen has the crown shorter with anterior margin more broadly rounded than in the female 
<typeStatus box="[151,253,297,323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">holotype</typeStatus>
; (2) the male has a distinct brown longitudinal band on the forewing, absent in 
<typeStatus box="[1159,1261,297,323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">holotype</typeStatus>
. Also, the male was collected at a high altitude site&gt; 
<quantity box="[580,666,333,359]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" unit="m" value="1.8">1,800m</quantity>
while the female 
<typeStatus box="[875,973,333,359]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">holotype</typeStatus>
was apparently collected near sea level. Sexual dimorphism in coloration (darker male, paler female) is common in leafhoppers, especially in Evacanthinae, e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1955" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[204,486,404,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Afronirvana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[204,340,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Afronirvana</emphasis>
Evans, 1955
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="Heller, 1972" authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="1972" box="[496,745,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Afrokana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[496,599,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Afrokana</emphasis>
Heller, 1972
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="Melichar, 1926" authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1926" box="[756,1051,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Synogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[756,874,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Synogonia</emphasis>
Melichar, 1926
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName box="[1108,1260,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Transvenosus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1108,1260,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Transvenosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dietrich, C. H." box="[1273,1432,405,431]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="455 - 487" refId="ref5482" refString="Dietrich, C. H. (2004) Phylogeny of the leafhopper subfamily Evacanthinae with a review of Neotropical species and notes on related groups (Hemiptera: Membracoidea: Cicadellidae). Systematic Entomology, 29, 455 - 487, https: // doi. prg / 10.1111 / j. 0307 - 6970.2004.00250. x" type="journal article" year="2004">Dietrich 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, Y. &amp; Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y." box="[151,357,441,467]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="431 - 441" refId="ref6102" refString="Wang, Y., Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y. (2017 b) Rewiew of two genera of Nirvanini leafhoppers (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae) from Africa. Zootaxa, 4231 (3), 431 - 441. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4231.3.9" type="journal article" year="2017">
Wang 
<emphasis box="[222,278,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">et al.</emphasis>
2017b
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, Y. &amp; Zhang, Y." box="[368,606,440,467]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="595 - 600" refId="ref5981" refString="Wang, Y. &amp; Zhang, Y. (2015) Transvenosus, a new genus in the leafhopper subfamily Evacanthinae (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae), with description of one new species. Zootaxa, 4052 (5), 595 - 600. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4052.5.9" type="journal article" year="2015">Wang &amp; Zhang 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Sexual dimorphism in the shape of the crown also occurs, as noted in 
<taxonomicName authority="Meshram &amp; Ramamurthy, 2013" authorityName="Meshram &amp; Ramamurthy" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Sophonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chandrai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Sophonia chandrai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meshram, N. M. &amp; Ramamurthy, V. V." box="[342,695,477,503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="224 - 230" refId="ref5725" refString="Meshram, N. M. &amp; Ramamurthy, V. V. (2013) Description of a new evacanthine leafhopper species Sophonia chandrai sp. nov., with new record of Chudania axona (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) from India. Zootaxa, 3717 (2), 224 - 230. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3717.2.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Meshram &amp; Ramamurthy, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Wang, Dietrich &amp; Zhang, 2018" authorityName="Wang, Dietrich &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2018" box="[747,1315,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Riseveinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinatus">
<emphasis box="[747,966,478,503]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">Riseveinus spinatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, Y. &amp; Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y." box="[972,1315,477,503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="259 - 266" refId="ref6162" refString="Wang, Y., Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y. (2018) Four new species of the leafhopper genus Riseveinus Li (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae) from China and Thailand. Zootaxa, 4508 (2), 259 - 266. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4508.2.8" type="journal article" year="2018">Wang, Dietrich &amp; Zhang, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Meshram, N. M. &amp; Ramamurthy, V. V." pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="224 - 230" refId="ref5725" refString="Meshram, N. M. &amp; Ramamurthy, V. V. (2013) Description of a new evacanthine leafhopper species Sophonia chandrai sp. nov., with new record of Chudania axona (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) from India. Zootaxa, 3717 (2), 224 - 230. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3717.2.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Meshram &amp; Ramamurthy 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, Y. &amp; Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y." box="[403,599,513,539]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="259 - 266" refId="ref6162" refString="Wang, Y., Dietrich, D. H. &amp; Zhang, Y. (2018) Four new species of the leafhopper genus Riseveinus Li (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae) from China and Thailand. Zootaxa, 4508 (2), 259 - 266. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4508.2.8" type="journal article" year="2018">
Wang 
<emphasis box="[475,531,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). However, because many leafhopper species appear to be endemic in high altitudes of the Serra da Mantiqueira (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Cavichioli, R. R. &amp; Mejdalani, G. L." box="[631,963,549,575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="963 - 971" refId="ref5401" refString="Cavichioli, R. R. &amp; Mejdalani, G. L. (1996) Scoposcartula Young: descriptions of a new species and of the female of S. flavovittata Mejdalani and redescription of S. concinna (Perty) comb. n. (Homoptera, Cicadellidae, Cicadellinae). Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 13 (4), 963 - 971. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0101 - 81751996000400017" type="journal article" year="1996">Cavichioli &amp; Mejdalani 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Takiya, D. M. &amp; Mejdalani, G. &amp; Felix, M." box="[974,1178,549,575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="175 - 183" refId="ref5924" refString="Takiya, D. M., Mejdalani, G. &amp; Felix, M. (2001) A new genus and species of Cicadellini (Hemiptera Cicadellidae Cicadellinae) from Southeastern Brazil. Tropical Zoology, 14 (1), 175 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03946975.2001.10531150" type="journal article" year="2001">
Takiya 
<emphasis box="[1056,1106,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="275">et al</emphasis>
. 2001
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Takiya, D. M. &amp; Cavichioli, R. R. &amp; Mejdalani, G." box="[1189,1247,549,575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref5864" refString="Takiya, D. M., Cavichioli, R. R. &amp; Mejdalani, G. (2003) Caragonia, a new genus of Cicadellini (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) from Southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 335 (1), 1 - 10. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 335.1.1" type="journal article" year="2003">2003</bibRefCitation>
) more collecting in the Atlantic Forest is needed to document more thoroughly the diversity of this group and the altitudinal ranges of species.
</paragraph>
